Anonymous Tue 10 Nov 2020 12:18:09 No.33981342 Report
Quoted By: >>33981496
>>33981165
I once saw a piece of Steampunk art where the vehicle in question didn't even seem to have a boiler. But one of the problems with the genre is that it doesn't really know what it stands for. It all started with the point of divergence being Charles Babbage's Difference Engine leading to an early revolution in computing, but most of the genre just seems to be this weird mish-mash where everything is steam operated ad Victorian, but mad science is also real and everyone has 21st century convictions. And half of it seems to sprinkle some magic in there for good measure.

The elephant in the room is, there is no reason for an early computing revolution to prevent the advent of the internal combustion engine. If anything, it would accelerate it. And the same goes for all other advanced technology. It's entirely predicated on the idea of what would happen if development of science and technology was maybe a few decades earlier than it actually happened. But that's more stuff like, would Karl Marx still devise communism if standard of living rises dramatically before he would otherwise have done so? Would the watershed WWI type conflict happen slightly earlier with earlier manufacturing of modern artillery and machineguns? Would they apply their new technology with the same carelessness as they applied real technology, leading to nasty consequences?

A story I came across recently was about a Victorian type society where genetic modification was discovered early, and the upper classes applied it with wild abandon, leading to a society of monstrosities that consider unaltered humans to be inhuman. That was an interesting take on it.

Ironically, steam power might be a bit player in its own genre if we're going by the original definition.

The aesthetic obsession really throws the whole genre for a loop. Years ago I read an interview with Cherie Priest, I believe her name was. She writes Steampunk books, but there's zombies. That's that while everything and the kitchen sink approach. One thing she said about it was that she came up with zombies as a way to explain the Steampunk fashion of wearing goggles and heavy gloves and such. It seems like such a weird thing to me, because protective gear is something you already absolutely want when everything is steam powered. I mean, if you have a watch that's powered by a tiny, little boiler with a tiny, little firebox, with a tiny, little coal shovel, I wouldn't want that thing to be touching bare skin.

Though, the other part I can't stand is how exaggerated the entire genre can get from time to time. You're never far from battle mechs powered by Tesla's undead brain in Steampunk. I'm down for stuff like steam powered land battleships and other nonsense straight from covers of Popular Mechanics or Mechanix Illustrated. But when you're making up stuff that wouldn't even make sense in the all but the highest tech science fiction, there's no real point to a steam setting in the first place.

Anonymous Tue 10 Nov 2020 15:07:04 No.33983092 Report
Quoted By:
>>33982927
Not
Him, that that’s why you establish restrictions of magic early. The second you rely on that shit later without foreshadowing, either by some early threat forcing its use or them using a spell of similar, if weaker, potency then yeah, I agree.
You establish someone can create fire and they later use it to detonate a powder keg at a finale, you’re fine. You establish someone can turn invisible if they stand still and have the villain rush at and impale a mannequin wearing the protagonists coat so they can stab the villain in the back, that’s them using their head AND magic.
You can maybe get away with them pulling off an advancement of an earlier spell. Like they’re not terribly accurate with a spell that can telekinetically throw arrows but they nail a one in a million shot, or psychically fuck up someone they’ve struggled to before because it was a last, desperate ditch attempt.
If you can’t stick to those sorts of self imposed restrictions, then there’s a very real risk of deus ex machines-ing shit. Magic isn’t a bad storytelling device since it can illuminate imaginative solutions, as mentioned in my first examples that may not come to a realistic imagination.
